# EEGLAB derivative — labelled .set files

One EEGLAB `.set` file per participant, containing the same minimally-processed
data as the released EDF (resting baseline + food categorization), with events
stored as EEGLAB-native string labels so they display correctly in EEGLAB.

## Why this layer exists
EEGLAB's native EDF import does not reliably parse event labels from EDF+
annotations or from events.tsv — it can render them as numeric codes (e.g. 0/1)
or NaN. These `.set` files store the event types directly as strings, so EEGLAB
shows meaningful labels with no extra steps. The repository-root EDFs remain the
canonical data; these files add no new information and are regenerable from them
(see ../../code/). Users of MNE-Python or FieldTrip can work directly from the
EDF + events.tsv and do not need this layer.

## Event labels in EEG.event.type
- `rest_eyesopen`, `rest_eyesclosed` — the two resting-baseline segments.
- `categorize/meat`, `categorize/veg` — categorization trials, by stimulus category.
The full trial-level record (response, response time, accuracy) is in the
corresponding events.tsv at the repository root.

## Contents
- 14 EEG channels; native 128 Hz; no filtering, resampling, or re-referencing.
- Standard 10-20 channel coordinates embedded in EEG.chanlocs. For scalp maps,
  run once after loading:  EEG = pop_chanedit(EEG, 'convert', {'cart2topo'});
- EEG.subject set; EEG.ref = 'CMS/DRL'.

The MATLAB-based EEGLAB is required to load .set files; the standalone/compiled
EEGLAB cannot run scripts but can open these files directly.
